AU  - Elisabet Rutström, E.
Y1  - 2008/08/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2008.00507.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1091
EP  - 1112
VL  - 49
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2008.00507.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We use field experiments to examine the temporal stability of risk preferences. Over a 17-month period, we elicited risk preferences from subjects chosen to be representative of the adult Danish population. During this period we revisited many of these subjects and repeated a risk aversion elicitation task. We find some variation in risk attitudes over time, but we do not detect a general tendency for risk attitudes to increase or decrease over a 17-month span. The results also suggest that risk preferences are state contingent with respect to personal finances.
ER  - 
